<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="102" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1436,1518,1725]" pageId="1" pageNumber="102">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,274,1518,1544]" pageId="1" pageNumber="102">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
The following combination of characters readily separates the Macaronesian species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Robineau-Desvoidy" authorityYear="1830" box="[1298,1436,1519,1545]" class="Insecta" family="Muscidae" genus="Limnophora" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="102" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1298,1436,1519,1545]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="102">Limnophora</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from other 
<taxonomicName box="[276,389,1555,1581]" class="Insecta" family="Muscidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="102" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Muscidae</taxonomicName>
: Small to medium sized muscids with paired subtriangular or trapezoid dark marks on tergites III and IV. Dorsocentral setae 3 or 4 behind the suture. Katepisternal setae 1 + 2. Prestomal teeth enlarged, modified for stabbing small prey. Prealar seta absent. Prosternum with setulae. Wing vein R 
<subScript attach="left" box="[1059,1067,1645,1659]" fontSize="6" pageId="1" pageNumber="102">1</subScript>
bare; radial node with dorsal and ventral setula(e). Ovipositor with complex hypoproct consisting of a large basal part with a pair of vertical extensions and a convex distal part covered in dense, up-curved setulae or spinules.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
